Take a flying tour of the new Bing Concert Hall, which opens tonight with performances by the San Francisco Symphony, St. Lawrence String Quartet and Stanford Chamber Chorale.
Prof. Chris Gerdes takes CBS for a ride in Shelley, the self-driving Audi he and his Stanford School of Engineering team helped design.
As classes resume in the new year, we look back on the people and ideas that defined Stanford in 2012.

Eggcellent: Using a "yolk-shell" nanoparticle design, scientists from Stanford and SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory have set a world record for energy storage in a sulfur cathode. Next step: combine with silicon anode to see if together they produce a lighter, longer-lasting battery for use in portable electronics.
"Once you think of yourself as a creative person, you make better decisions." David Kelley, d.school head and IDEO founder, talks about unlocking creativity with Charlie Rose of 60 Minutes.

As Stanford Football prepares for the 99th Annual Rose Bowl Game, we look back on a few of the moments that made 2012 an exciting year for Stanford athletes and fans.

It's tempting to look back on a year at Stanford by recounting major milestones. But life on "the Farm" is more than move-in day or Big Game. Below are a few of the quieter moments that made campus what it was in 2012. Unless otherwise noted, all photos were taken by L.A. Cicero of the Stanford News Service.

Alumnus Blake English contemplated a career in military defense. Then, inspired by a trip to the Monterey Bay Aquarium, he veered into a very different type of design work - this one involving air-swimming sharks and hovering fairies.

Laughter, tears, panic and occasional exclamations of triumph bring the Product Realization Lab to cacophonous life the last few weeks of fall quarter, as mechanical engineering students drag their class projects from concept to varying degrees of real-world materialization. The pieces, in all their quirk and glory, went on display at the d. school Monday afternoon.

A day after students in “Legal Aspects of Autonomous Driving” went for a spin in Google’s self-driving car,  Stanford Libraries took on the entire 65-year archives of Road & Track Magazine. Sorry, Mr. Page, but this experimental Lincoln might be hard to beat. http://stanford.io/T561ay

Congratulations to professors Brian Kobilka and Alvin Roth, who were in Stockholm today for the Nobel Prize Award Ceremony. King Carl XVI Gustaf of Sweden presented them with their medals, in chemistry and economic sciences respectively.

Through an exploration of Istanbul's back alleys and shantytowns, Stanford students got an up-close-and-personal look at a city caught between a glorious past and a global future: http://stanford.io/TPEKYP    Photo courtesy of Ali Yaycioğlu
Yesterday's CS106A lecture was given the unremarkable title of "class on special topic." It turned out to be a surprise visit from Mark Zuckerberg, CEO and co-founder of Facebook.

Freshmen Matthew Volk and Mark Nishimura were busy launching rockets for their classical mechanics lab when they were approached by a curious passerby. The man, who posed a few questions and then wandered on, was later revealed to be Professor Emeritus Douglas Osheroff, co-recipient of the 1996 Nobel physics prize.    Volk's response: "Wow. I tried to make my answers to his questions really simple so he could understand them. I forget where I am sometimes.” http://stanford.io/YNyBlK    Photo by L.A. Cicero / Stanford News Service

"Black swan" is a term that swims freely through public discourse in the aftermath of disaster. It's meant to define rare, perfect-storm events (the financial meltdown, for example) we don't have to blame ourselves for not anticipating. But one Stanford School of Engineering professor thinks the label is simply a poor excuse for bad risk-management. Do you?

Plain old carbon is one of the most abundant elements on earth - but that characteristic makes it an exciting plaything for researchers working on novel nanomaterials. MIT Technology Review describes the first all-carbon solar cells, built by Prof. Zhenan Bao.
California voters approved Proposition 36 last week, overturning the state's three-strikes law. Slate.com profiles the Stanford Law professors and students who were behind the initiative.

A team of researchers at Stanford and SLAC National Accelerator Laboratory has developed a new battery technology that may one day be a cost-effective alternative to standard batteries. A Stanford study finds that the university's alumni and faculty have created 39,900 active companies. If these companies collectively formed an independent nation, its estimated economy would be the world’s 10th largest, generating world revenues of $2.7 trillion annually.

To everyone in the Stanford community, both near and afar, we wish you a safe and happy Fourth of July!

After 10 years of patient research in Costa Rica, Stanford researchers may have found a way to use land for agriculture while still preserving biodiversity.

"It's a big privilege to be trusted with something like this."  For one Stanford course, 21 students went beyond pretend scenarios and practiced real philanthropy, giving away a combined $100,000 to six different nonprofits on the last day of class.

Traditional cookstoves cause heavy pollution in the developing world, leading to millions of deaths. Safer stoves are available, but Stanford researchers say few people buy them because the newer models aren't designed to give people what they really want.

Yesterday, the Stanford community brought together their tools and know-how to observe a once-in-a-lifetime event: Venus crossing the Sun in Earth's sky.  Photo: L.A. Cicero / Stanford News Service  For more images:  http://news.stanford.edu/news/2012/june/venus-sun-slideshow-060612.html

"Each neuron behaves like a player in a band."  Stanford neuroscientists and electrical engineers have proposed an elegant new theory for physical movement - one based on combining rhythmic signals in the motor cortex.

Stanford Live, the University's rebranded performing arts presenting organization, will elevate the live performance experience on campus in conjunction with its new state-of-the-art facility, the Bing Concert Hall. The inaugural season kicks off in January 2013!

When there’s a story on campus that needs to be told, the Stanford Storytelling Project is on it.  “One of the project's main goals is to help us understand just how deeply conditioned we are by stories” -Jonah Willihnganz, founder and director.
Stanford researchers set up motion-activated cameras right outside Stanford campus to observe the nearby wildlife.  Here's what they found.

Fast food is undoubtedly an American creation, but its contents – hamburgers, french fries, and the like – have international roots.  Check out Prof. Jurasky's history of ketchup, which begins 500 years ago in China.

Bluefin tuna caught on California shores contain low levels of radioactivity, which scientists have linked to the 2011 Japanese nuclear meltdown. These findings break new waves in using radioactive elements to track migration routes.  "This is an example of how events don't happen in a vacuum" – Daniel Madigan, PhD candidate
Just another lovely spring sunset at Stanford.  Photo: Tamer Shabani '13, www.tamershabani.com

"The dream is a computer that is thinking about what you want and what you mean- rather than what you said."  Two Stanford professors have created a mathematical model that helps predict how language is being used in social situations - taking us a step closer to computers that will understand sarcasm, idioms, and hyperbole.

"Dick Lyman was a man of great strength, integrity, common sense and good humor. It was a privilege to know him, and I am deeply saddened by his death. His impact on Stanford was profound. Stanford researchers may have discovered a powerful tool in the fight against cancer. An antibody that blocks the "don't eat me" protein on most cancerous cells is showing promise as a new form of treatment and, with the help of a $20 million grant, Professor Weissman and his team are now moving on to human trials.

According to Prof. Field, we're in for longer, more intense heat waves and storms.  Field urges that preparations be made not only for this weather, but for changes like this that global warming will continue to bring about.

"Stanford University produces the talent and the attitude to start tech companies."  Pinpointing the 'capital' of Silicon Valley may be complicated, but Stanford has certainly played a vital role in its growth.

"We want to provide an environment that feels like less of a shelter and more of a home."  Stanford students of the homeless advocacy group Night Outreach establish the Hotel de Zink Women's Shelter which houses, counsels, and provides for women in need.

From Elvis lyrics to jokes on the Big Bang Theory, pop culture (and American tutors) give international students the opportunity to learn how to speak 'American.'  This quarter, 100 students enrolled in the program, meeting with a one-on-one tutor every week for an hour.

Prof. Snyder takes a brave plunge into his own genome, finding an unwelcome surprise: diabetes.   However, discovering this allows him to uncover distinct links between his genes and the disease, breaking ground in a new field of 'personalized medicine.'

Epic installation of Richard Serra's sculpture “Sequence” at the Iris & B. Gerald Cantor Center for Visual Arts at Stanford University.   “Sequence,” which measures 67 feet long, 42 feet wide, and 13 feet high, is composed of contoured steel and weighs more than 200 tons. Considered one of Serra’s greatest achievements, the work will be on view outdoors for the first time since its creation in 2006. The sculpture is on loan from the Doris and Don Fisher Collection until 2016.

Stanford Associate Professor Yi Cui and his research team have developed a battery that runs on a combination of ocean and river water. The team estimates that if all the world's rivers were put to use, their batteries could supply about 13 percent of current global energy consumption.

Pink, yellow, green and red powder flew through the air at Sand Hill Field for Holi, an annual celebration sponsored by the charitable organization Asha Stanford. Also called the Festival of Colors, Holi is an Indian tradition heralding the arrival of spring. The ritual of spattering one another with brightly tinted gulal signifies putting aside differences, shedding inhibitions and embracing the spirit of the season. Proceeds from the event, which draws several thousand people from around the Bay Area, benefit education-related projects in India.    Photograph by Toni Gauthier

Education in the arts and humanities is the foundation of a liberal arts education and serves three important roles. First, it prepares graduates to deal with the complexity, diversity, and ambiguity of human societies. Second, it draws out and develops personal creativity. Third, the arts bridge all cultures, providing access to the experience of people in other times and places. In the contemporary world in which Stanford graduates will lead and inspire, understanding complexity, finding creative solutions to problems, and navigating the richness of human culture are essential capabilities.

Stanford University is seeking solutions for society's most formidable problems. New research initiatives are breaking down traditional academic boundaries and bringing together collaborative teams of experts to address major societal issues, including human health, environmental sustainability, and international peace and security.
